	   <a name=101732171021643></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101732171021643><tr><td id=headerrow><span id=sj>Money Making the Monkly Way.</span></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=119937><span id= >Basilisk</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>3 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Mar 28th 8:25 AM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2> I would post this as a reply to the fellow named monkkey, but I'm having slight server troubles. Hope this works. Also, I am now a level 25 monk, and this post is based on my limited experience.<br><br> Making money is one of the more challenging aspects of Everquest for a monk, thanks almost entirely to our weight limits. Many a time will pass when your group will kill that rare spawn who drops a great item for selling, and no one else will even want it, but you sure can't pick it up without deserting your group. It's as bad as making three to five bank runs an hour totaling about 20 minutes of wasted run time just to empty your change into the bank! Oh well, so it goes. This does not mean that money can't be made by a monk, of course. It just means we have to work a little harder. At level 25, I currently have around 550pp. All told, I've probably made about 1.8k-2k in this characters life. Of course I could have made more, and many people do, but I have nice items for the most part and have a great time with my character, so I'm content. {though I wasn't content the time I saw a guy selling a spider-fur belt for 150pp and I happened to be recently broke. ARRGHH!!!} Here is my amateur advice on making money;<br><br>1.} Sell droppable quest items that are in high demand : When I was young, I tried selling bone granite powder. This takes way too long to gain. As an Iksar, I think the best items in this category to sell are fingers from the fingered skeleton in Kurns. Of course, you'll want to complete the quest yourself first, and since they're lore, you'll actually have to. Auction the fingers off in Kurns and in the Field of Bone to other monks who want to save time and effort by simply buying them. I had a level sixty monk who was just doing his quests offer me three hundred pp for a full set of four. I advise selling mostly to characters of this nature, as younger characters won't have unlimited resources and might enjoy the experience more themselves. Kurns is great fun. Sometimes I feel quite nice and give sets away to monks camping the fingers, but it's when desperate for money, the chance is there.<br><br>2.} Utility items : Bonechips, silks and silk swatches are best of this category. All can be attained quite easily {in order of difficulty easiest first} and sell to higher level Necros/tailors at going rates. I typically sell bonechips at 4pp a stack, sometimes cutting deals with large orders. I rarely have too much trouble selling them in FOB, Oasis ans other such low level adventure zones. Pelts, silks and silk swatches usually sell better in EC.<br><br>3.} Giants : I like to solo Forest giants these days. They drop average change and occasioanly weapons which sell to merchants for around 10-50pp. Not terrible, the weapons are not exceptionally rare. I find maybe four items to every 20 giants. Maybe 60-75pp to every 20 giants. Also, many times you will be in WW at the same time as a Grachnist camper who will /ooc away the gloves, which you can auction off quite nicely.<br><br>4.} Items : If you happen to acquire items that you don't need, sell them! Well, often I give away lower level but decent items to new characters, but that's besides the point. Check merchants as well, sometimes you get great deals. I once bought a runic carver for 8pp off of a merchant, and bought my pair of coterie general boots {which are awesome} for 116pp.<br><br>5.} Backpacks ; I've never tried it myself, but I often hear that tailoring backpacks has excellent payoff. I don't have much info on this though.<br><br>6.} Services : Many a high level character in EQ simply dosn't know their way around Kunark, or needs an item transfer to his friend or twink. Be nice, offer to guide or assist them. Only if they ask, of course. It's annoying for higher level players to be plagued with sychophantic tells. Often, your generosity will be rewarded. If it is not, be polite, bow and be on your way. I once had a fellow have me run around for about an hour transfering items and when I was done, he rewarded me with a cloth shirt at level 16. I also once had a fellow ask me to do a quick item transfer, five minutes later,he gives me a drolvarg mantle. In both cases, I was grateful and polite. It's how you play the game.<br><br>Those are a few pointers, hope they help you.<br><br>Izelcoatl<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
